bio: Public Library

I'm a scientist (research group leader) currently working at the School of Chemistry, The University of Sydney. More specifically, I'm an ARC DECRA and University of Sydney Vice Chancellor's Fellow.

My research focuses on designing self-assembled molecular materials that can undergo controlled morphological transformations in response to external stimuli. I use synthetic chemistry and molecular self-assembly to try and make 'smart' materials that can sense their environments and respond in specific ways, targeting applications in advanced healthcare materials (e.g., accelerated wound healing) and plastics with in-built sensors.

Sometimes I need tools in the lab that can't be purchased or are unreasonably expensive... so I design and 3D print them instead! In the spirit of open-access science, I hope uploading some of these designs ends up being useful to other people.

I am dual qualified as a "A" grade Electrician and a Electronic Technician. I have been working in this field since 1980.
I Injured my back in 2011 and have a permanent nerve injury. In 2013 my boss decided I no longer can function properly at my job so I was made redundant. My condition got worst, my GP recommended I find a new hobby to focus on to control my depression and pain, so I took up 3D printing. I purchased my first 3D printer late 2014 which was a CTC Dual Extruder type. Little did I know what I was getting myself into. It all looked like fun on the internet, but a totally different in reality. My doctor was right I didn't have much time to think about any thing else. Being a service engineer most of my life, the 3D printer had to work to my standards and expectations. But of course, the Printer I purchased needed a lot of work to get it up to scratch. In 2014 there were not many avenues to search up for advice and being a novice at that time I really didn't know where to access the information. It took a good 9 to 10 months of liaising back and forth with CTC to nut out problems. I carried out plenty of different mods to the printer until I finally got the printer setup to print to a standard I was happy with. Shortly after an opportunity arise to purchase a cheap Tevo BW. I purchased my Tevo late 2016. It had a good build but assembling the printer also made me aware that this printer, also needed work for improvement. The amount of problems I had with the Tevo, what can I say. There were several times of shear frustration that I nearly scrapped the Tevo. Constant fault after fault, due to low tolerances in the electronic design. Current handling capacity of the Tevo was very poor. It took almost a year to resolve the on going faults. After nutting out the problems, I'm happy to say my Tevo Bw prints great now.
I'm not a big fan of cute trinkets. Having said that I do on the occasion print stuff out for my kids and relatives. I mostly focus on Engineering designs and workable models. I use SolidWorks to design my projects. I am self taught, I'm not very good at it but I learn more every time I use it. It takes me long to complete projects form start to finish due to my condition. But at the completion, Without sounding weird, satisfaction oozes over me when the project come together. I hope you like some of my projects I will do my best to keep producing new enjoyable projects for 3D printing. I look forward to hearing you comments and ideas. I am open to all improvements and ideas as my mind is not as sharp as it use to be. Thank you for taking the time to read my BIO. Happy Printing...
